PCA

  1. (20 points) Perform a PCA analysis. While doing so:

    • Which function did you use?

    We decided to use the prcomp function.

    • Did you scale your data?

    Yes, we scaled the data. Scaling the data is very important when it comes to PCA and distance based algorithms (ie clustering).

It seems like five is the best number of components based on the cumulative proportion.

heart.pca = prcomp(heart[,-c(2,3,6,7,9,11,13,14)], scale=TRUE, center=TRUE)

  1. (20 points) Looking at biplot and scree plots, were you able to reduce the dimensionality of your data?

It seems like the elbow of the scree plot occurs at the second component. Dimensionality wasnt a big concern for this data set because a lot of the variables needed to be removed due to their categorical nature (only 6 remained) and reducing the dimensionality through PCA only removed one component. It only reduced it by one since the first couple of components didnt strongly explain the variances. It makes sense that to be able to explain the variability in the data we need to use at least 5 principle components. Overall, we were not able to reduce the dimensionality very much; however, this was expected since the data is not high dimensional.

biplot(heart.pca)

fviz_eig(heart.pca)

fviz_pca_var(heart.pca,
             col.var = "contrib", # Color by contributions to the PC
             gradient.cols = c("#00AFBB", "#E7B800", "#FC4E07"),
             repel = TRUE     # Avoid text overlapping
             )

  1. (15 points) What did you gain by doing a PCA?

In this case, performing principle component analysis allowed us to gain a better understanding of the structure of the data, and we were able to determine that we do not have a very high dimensional data set. It only removed one variable component from the model, slightly reducing the dimensionality of the data. We are also able to see that almost all the variables have a very large impact on explaining variability in the data as we can only drop one of the principle components and remain above 85% of the variance being explained. It also eliminated any multicollinearity concerns that was evident in the correlation plot above.

Clustering

  1. (25 points) Using principle components corresponding to at least 85% of the variation, perform a mixture model clustering algorithm. Which algorithm you chose and why? How did you determine the number of clusters?

We plotted the five different components to see their distributions. For the mixture modeling clustering algorithm, the team decided to use Gaussian Mixture Modeling algorithm. The individual distributions were relatively normal, and this is a useful function to use with that type of distribution. The team tested 2 clusters since there is most likely a heart disease cluster and a non heart disease cluster. This is actually confirmed with the data set target/condition column. However, we could have made an educated guess about this. When the team ran the function without specifying the number of clusters in order to determine the optimal number of clusters, it determined that the optimal number of clusters is 5. However, this model has a higher BIC score. Overall, the team determined the number of clusters from the data dictionary, best judgement, and BIC score. The team feels more comfortable with 2 clusters based on this information.

cluster = data.frame(heart.pca$x[,1:5])

ggplot(cluster, aes(x = heart.pca$x[,1] )) +
  geom_density() 

ggplot(cluster, aes(x = heart.pca$x[,2] )) +
  geom_density() 

ggplot(cluster, aes(x = heart.pca$x[,3] )) +
  geom_density()  

ggplot(cluster, aes(x = heart.pca$x[,4] )) +
  geom_density()  

ggplot(cluster, aes(x = heart.pca$x[,5] )) +
  geom_density()  

#2 cluster model

8. (20 points) What is/are your finding(s) based on your clustering algorithm? Explain your findings to a nontechnical audience, i.e., your parents or siblings.

Clustering is used to identify subgroups within unlabeled data. Unlabeled data means that there isnt a column that identifies which group the row belongs to, and the clustering algorithm is in charge of finding those hidden groups. The data set that we dealt with involved variables related to heart disease. Based on the clustering algorithm we performed above, there appears to be two distinct groups within this data set that are similar to each other. Out of the almost 300 data points that we have, the algorithm split the data almost exactly in half to comprise the two clusters. We believe that the two clusters are people with heart disease vs people without heart disease.
